entry.content:
Problem:
ui/base/x/x11_global_shortcut_listener.cc
bool XGlobalShortcutListener::RegisterAccelerator(KeyboardCode key_code,...) {
...
  auto keysym = XKeysymForWindowsKeyCode(key_code, false);
  auto keycode = connection_->KeysymToKeycode(keysym);
}
after XKeysymForWindowsKeyCode(...) and KeysymToKeycode(...), if the input argument key_code=0,  the value keycode will 
be transformed to an UnExpeced keycode!!! And an unexpected shortcut is registered.
On my Ubuntu 23.04/GNOME(X11),  keycode is transformed to 204 and will make Alt_L shortcut registered. Other OSs may be different, LMDE6 will be BackSpace.
We can use command "xmodmap -pk | grep ${KEYCODE}" to check keysym for KEYCODE.

To Reproduce:
My test code keysymbug.c(Attacehed), compile with "gcc -Wno-deprecated-declarations -o keysymbug keysymbug.c -lX11".
Run keysymbug(test code), will produce output:
src keycode(0x0)->keysym(0x0:(null))
keysym(0x0)->translated to keycode(204:0xcc)
!!!Warning: keycode 0 tranformed to valued keycode(204:0xcc)
You can use shell command 'xmodmap -pk| grep 204' find key meanging.
1: keycode(204:0xcc) ->transformed to keysym(0xffe9:Alt_L)
!!!Warning: keycode 0 transformed to meaningful keysym:(65513:0xffe9:Alt_L)

Solution:
add extra check:
@@ -86,6 +86,11 @@ bool XGlobalShortcutListener::RegisterAccelerator(KeyboardCode key_code,
   auto keysym = XKeysymForWindowsKeyCode(key_code, false);
   auto keycode = connection_->KeysymToKeycode(keysym);

+  // if key_code is 0, keycode may be transformed to unexpected key.
+  if (key_code == ui::KeyboardCode::VKEY_UNKNOWN && keysym == 0) {
+    return false;
+  }
