The TimelineModel will subtract 1 from line numbers in certain events to take them from 1 index to 0 indexed:

```
      case RecordType.EvaluateScript:
      case RecordType.CompileScript:
      // @ts-ignore fallthrough intended.
      case RecordType.CacheScript: {
        if (typeof eventData['lineNumber'] === 'number') {
          --eventData['lineNumber'];
        }
        if (typeof eventData['columnNumber'] === 'number') {
          --eventData['columnNumber'];
        }
      }
```

In various helpers that linkify and output a URL plus line/col numbers, 1 is then added to the output. It is expected in our data that we model the numbers as 0 indexed, but trace events work off 1 indexing.

The legacy TimelineModel mutates these events to fix this, but we want to remove the old model.

Rather than mutate the events, let's instead create a helper inside TimelineUIUtils (where most of the UI generation logic exists) to correctly subtract one and return the "right" (0-indexed) numbers for events that need it (which is the 3 events listed up there).

Chrome 126.0.6435.0

Steps to reproduce:

1. Open DevTools in Chrome 
2. Enable Protocol Monitor experiment in DevTools settings
3. Open Protocol Monitor pane
4. Navigate to example.com
5. Navigate to the DevTools console tab, run the following script to create many elements

for (var i = 0; i <= 10000; i++) {
            const button = document.createElement('button');
            button.textContent = i;
            document.body.appendChild(button);
        }

6. Run the following commands for the main target (use the dropdown in Protocol monitor to select the target) "Accessibility.disable" and "Overlay.disable" by pasting the command into the Protocol Monitor's input and pressing Enter. (this commands remove DevTools-retained a11y caches).

7. Runs the following script searching for buttons using getAccessibleName and getAccessibleRole bindings (they call into blink's Element::computedRole, Element::computedName)


```
const returnedNodes = [];

console.log("running")

const bindings = {
    getAccessibleRole,
    getAccessibleName
}

function collect(
    contextNodes,
    selector
) {
for (const contextNode of contextNodes) {
  let match = true;

  if (selector.role) {
    const role = bindings.getAccessibleRole(contextNode);
    if (selector.role !== role) {
      match = false;
    }
  }

  if (selector.name) {
    const name = bindings.getAccessibleName(contextNode);
    if (selector.name !== name) {
      match = false;
    }
  }

  if (match) {
    returnedNodes.push(contextNode);
  }

  const childNodes = [];
  for (const child of contextNode.children) {
    if (child instanceof HTMLElement) {
      childNodes.push(child);
    }
  }

  collect(childNodes, selector);
}
}

collect([document.body], {
    role: 'button',
    name: undefined,
});

console.log(returnedNodes)
```


Expected result:

The querying is slow because a11y cache is re-created for each call.

Actual result:

OOM crash happens. Crash ID https://goto.google.com/crash/db479b13e5e28c42

Note: this is a manual reproducible example but this issue affects mostly automation clients that didn't turn on the a11y caches.
